00:00:09.090 --> 00:00:11.070
MATT PARKER: See, most people
forgot about the Rubik's Cube

00:00:11.070 --> 00:00:13.270
back in the '80s, so it had
its heyday and then

00:00:13.270 --> 00:00:13.550
disappeared.

00:00:13.550 --> 00:00:15.770
But mathematicians remain
obsessed with it.

00:00:15.770 --> 00:00:17.340
KATIE STECKLES: I mean, people
probably are aware that there

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:19.250
is some math involved
in Rubik's Cube.

00:00:19.250 --> 00:00:21.990
JAMES GRIME: The reason I not
interested in the Rubik's Cube

00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:24.130
was I wanted to use as
a teaching tool.

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:28.530
In my day job I study something
called group theory.

00:00:28.530 --> 00:00:31.100
KATIE STECKLES: If you go to
any kind of Wikipedia page

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:33.270
about anything to do with group
theory, there will be,

00:00:33.270 --> 00:00:35.460
in the top corner, a picture
of a Rubik's Cube.

00:00:35.460 --> 00:00:38.220
And the reason for that is that
it has got quite a nice

00:00:38.220 --> 00:00:40.150
example of a group associated
with it.

00:00:40.150 --> 00:00:43.520
And the group is the number of
different combinations that

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:44.590
there are on the Rubik's Cube.

00:00:44.590 --> 00:00:46.310
It's all the different
ways that you can

00:00:46.310 --> 00:00:47.570
scramble up a cube.

00:00:47.570 --> 00:00:50.610
JAMES GRIME: So for example,
if you had a square, and I

00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:54.000
turn it a quarter turn, you
still get a square, don't you?

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.330
And even if I take a square, and
I flip it over, you still

00:00:57.330 --> 00:00:58.120
get square, right?

00:00:58.120 --> 00:00:59.700
So it has that symmetry.

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:01.720
Now, this is what I study.

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:04.410
So I started to learn how the
Rubik's Cube worked, because

00:01:04.410 --> 00:01:06.590
the mathematics is the same.

00:01:06.590 --> 00:01:11.220
So if I turn this here, the
right hand side a quarter

00:01:11.220 --> 00:01:13.460
turn, I can do that.

00:01:13.460 --> 00:01:16.400
I do it twice, you get a half
turn. you do it get three

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:20.080
times, that's equal to
a quarter turn in

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:21.670
the opposite direction.

00:01:21.670 --> 00:01:26.480
If you do it four times, you get
back to where you started.

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:27.175
LUCAS GARRON: Hey,
